Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read what you can and cannot do

This page gives you guidance on how to stay safely in Lebanon as a visitor, if you are unable to return to the UK.
Everyone should comply with the measures put in place in Lebanon to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
Moving around in Lebanon
There are local travel restrictions in place in Lebanon.
For information on entering Lebanon, see Entry Requirements.
Public measures
The Lebanese authorities have extended the lock-down until at least 24 May 2020.
On 12 May 2020, the Government announced a tightening of COVID-19 restrictions, coming into force at 19:00 on 13 May 2020, until 05:00 on 18 May 2020. The announcement reinforces the requirement for individuals to remain at home unless it is absolutely necessary, and reinforces the ban on gatherings in public and private places.
Individuals must remain at home and restrict movement to essential movement only. Those over the age of 65 years old are advised to stay home and not go out unless absolutely necessary.
Public and private gatherings are banned.
There should be no movement from 1800 to 0500.
Face masks covering the mouth and nose must be worn when outside the home.
Individuals must maintain a safe distance from one another and avoid crowded areas.
Traffic is banned between 1800 and 0500. Vehicles with license plates ending in 1,3,5,7 or 9 are only permitted to move on Mondays, Wednesdays, Fridays. Vehicles with license plates ending in 0,2,4,6 or 8 are only permitted to move on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Saturdays. No cars are allowed to move on Sunday.. There are exemptions for military and security forces, the International Committee for the Red Cross, diplomatic and specific health and food industry related vehicles.
Private cars containing more than two people may be stopped.
All public transport is suspended.
There may be difficulties accessing taxis
Public departments, banks (ATMs and electronic transfers are functioning), municipalities, unions, universities, public and private schools are closed, with the exception of core institutions, including security agencies, hospitals, and pharmacies.
Lebanese authorities may issue fines, impose road blocks, or imprison those violating these restrictions for up to three years. You should comply with all local restrictions introduced by the Lebanese authorities and obey instructions of the security forces. These restrictions may be changed at short notice.
Keep up to date with information from your tour operator, transport or accommodation provider on the impact on any existing travel plans. If you need further information about entry requirements, contact the local immigration authorities or the nearest Lebanese embassy.
Visas
If you are concerned about your visa expiring please contact General Security on 1717 or +961 (0) 1424668 for advice. General Security are currently extending visas and not issuing fines for visas that have expired since Covid-19 restrictions have been introduced.
Health
For contact details of English speaking doctors visit our list of healthcare providers.
Your emotional and mental wellbeing is important. Read guidance on how to look after your mental wellbeing and mental health.
View Health for further details on healthcare in Lebanon.
